Lament -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection of essays examines the motifs of darkness, depression, and descent in both literal and figurative manifestations within a variety of Anglo-Saxon texts, including the Old English Consolation of Philosophy, Beowulf, Guthlac, The Junius Manuscript, The Wonders of the East, and The Battle of Maldon. Essays deal with such topics as cosmic emptiness, descent into the grave, and recurrent grief. In their analyses, the essays reveal the breadth of this imagery in Anglo-Saxon literature as it is used to describe thought and emotion, as well as the limits to knowledge and perception. The volume investigates the intersection between the burgeoning interest in trauma studies and darkness and the representation of the mind or of emotional experience within Anglo-Saxon literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aLight and darkness in literature. 4aAngelsachsen. 4aDepression. 4aDunkelheit. 4aPsyche. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon.  aDarkness.  aDepression.  aMind.1 aAnlezark, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorysławski, Rafał, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Amy W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKears, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Gwendolyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichelet, Fabienne L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMissuno, Filip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMomma, Haruko, ec